SIMPLE: straggle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Straggle
<hw>Strag"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Straggled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Straggling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq.
of OE. <ets>straken</ets> to roam, to stroke. See <er>Stroke</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wander from the direct
course or way; to rove; to stray; to wander from the line of march or
desert the line of battle; <as>as, when troops are on the march, the men
should not <ex>straggle</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wander at large; to roam idly about; to
ramble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wolf spied out a <qex>straggling</qex> kid.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To escape or stretch beyond proper limits, as the
branches of a plant; to spread widely apart; to shoot too far or widely
in growth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trim off the small, superfluous branches on each side of the hedge
that <qex>straggle too far out</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be dispersed or separated; to occur at
intervals.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Straggling</xex> pistol shots.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They came between Scylla and Charybdis and the
<qex>straggling</qex> rocks.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Straggle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Straggle
<hw>Strag"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of straggling.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Straggler</ent>⟦br⟧
